<html>
<body>

<center>
<b>CONVERT IERS POLE FILES TO BERNESE FORMAT</b>
<p>Program: POLUPD
</center>
<hr width="100%">

<a name="ENVIRONMENT"   default="%% %%"></a>
<a name="CAMPAIGN"      default=""></a>
<a name="SESSION_TABLE" default="SESSIONS"></a>
<a name="YR4_INFO"      default="$Y+0"></a>
<a name="SES_INFO"      default="$S+0"></a>
<a name="USR_INFO"      default="${USER}"></a>

<p><b>GENERAL DESCRIPTION</b>
<p>
This program creates or updates a file containing the Earth Rotation
Parameter (ERP) information. The information is taken from one or more
input files given in almost any format (e.g. Bernese format, IERS
Bulletin A or B format, etc.) and is written to the Bernese output file
specified.
<br>
If equal epochs in different input files are found the record from the last
file (in alphabetical order!) will be written to the output file. It is
recommended to convert the files one by one; otherwise, make sure that time
intervals covered by the input files do not overlap.

<p><hr>

<p><b>POLUPD 1: Input/Output Files</b>

<a name="SHOWGEN" default="1"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL FILES</b>
<p><b>Show all general files:</b>
Check this box to get a list of the general input files used by this program
as well as the currently active campaign, session, and session table.

<br><br>

<a name="ERPFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>INPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Bernese formatted ERP files:</b>
This entry field defines the input files written in Bernese format.
Leave the field blank if you don't want to use Bernese ERP files as input.

<p><i>Remark:</i>
It is recommended to convert the files one by one; otherwise, make sure
that time intervals covered by the input files do not overlap.

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.ERP">Example</a>.

<a name="IEPFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>Foreign formatted ERP files:</b>
This entry field defines the input files written in a foreign format (see
<a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.IEP">Example</a> of a file from CODE). About 20
formats are supported and automatically identified. You may
read pole information files originating from IERS (C04, Bulletin A, Bulletin
B), from IGS, from all IGS analysis centers. Various older format versions
are supported. Formats specifying UT1-UTC, UT1R-UTC, UT1-TAI, etc., are
automatically converted. An error message is issued if a format is unknown.
<br>
Leave the field blank if you don't want to use "Foreign formatted ERP files"
as input.

<p><i>Remark:</i>
It is recommended to convert the files one by one; otherwise, make sure
that time intervals covered by the input files do not overlap.

<br><br>

<a name="OUTFIL" default=""></a>
<p><b>RESULT FILE</b>
<p><b>Bernese formatted ERP file (out):</b>
Enter the name of the resulting Earth Rotation Parameter file in Bernese
format. If a file with this name does already exist it will be updated,
otherwise a new file will be created.

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.ERP">Example</a>

<br><br>

<a name="SYSODEF" default="1"></a>
<a name="SYSOUT" default="POLUPD"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL OUTPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Program output:</b>
You can choose to have the program output written to a separate file for each
program run (checkbox marked), or specify a common name for all program runs.
<br>
If you mark the checkbox, the filename will correspond to the program name
with an extension containing a counter (Lnn), which is automatically
incremented for each program run. If the counter reaches the maximum value, it
is automatically reset, and existing files will be overwritten.
The maximum value can be set in
<b>Menu &gt; Configure &gt; Program Names</b>, option "Maximum program output
file number".
<br>
If the checkbox is unmarked, you have to specify a name for the program
output file. This allows to characterize the program run, e.g., by using the
day and year (<tt>$YD+0</tt>) in the filename.

<a name="ERRMRG" default="0"></a>
<a name="SYSERR" default="ERROR"></a>
<p><b>Error messages:</b>
You can choose to have error messages written into the program's output
file (see above), or specify a separate file to which error messages are
written.

<p><hr>

<p><b>POLUPD 1.1: General Files</b>

<a name="OFFFIL" default=""></a>
<b>GENERAL INPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Pole offset coefficients: </b>
This file contains the pole offset information that is used to transform
C04-pole and Rapid-pole information to the actual epoch (e.g., C04 ITRF 1988
to C04 ITRF 1996). Until the revision of the generation of C04-pole and
Rapid-pole information by the IERS in 1997 this file had to be update every
year to introduce the new constants given in the annual report of the
IERS.
<br>
Today the pole offsets are <i>no longer required</i> because the IERS
pole series are kept consistent with the ITRF in near-real-time based on
measurements provided by the space geodetic techniques.
<br>
You do not need this file at all if you use IGS pole information or the
C04- or the Rapid-pole from the
<a href="/$X/DOC/README_AIUB_AFTP.TXT">anonymous ftp</a>
account of AIUB (Astronomical Institute of the University of Bern).
<br>
Leave the field empty if you do not want to correct for pole offsets.

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/POLOFF.">$X/GEN/POLOFF.</a>

<p><i>Default value:</i> empty

<a name="GPSUTC" default="GPSUTC.">
<p><b>GPS-UTC seconds:</b></A>
This file contains a table of all the leap seconds introduced during
the last ten years. This information is used to transform the
pole information from Bulletin A and B (see above) into the Bernese
pole format. You have to modify this file whenever a new leap
second is announced by the IERS. You do not need this file at all if
you use IGS pole information or the C04- or the Rapid-pole from the
<a href="/$X/DOC/README_AIUB_AFTP.TXT">anonymous ftp</a> account of AIUB
(Astronomical Institute of the University of Bern).

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/GPSUTC.">$X/GEN/GPSUTC.</a>

<p><i>Default value:</i>  GPSUTC.

<p><hr>

<p><b>POLUPD 2: Options</b>

<a name="TITLE" default=""></a>
<p><b>HEADER INFORMATION</b>
<p><b>Title:</b>
This title line will be printed as header comment into the program output
and will be saved in the result file to document the program run.
The title should characterize the program run by, e.g., giving the most
important options used and the session.

<a name="NUTMOD" default="IAU2000R06"></a>
<p><b>Nutation model:</b>
Bernese ERP files specify the nutation model used for the generation of
the file. If the corresponding string is found in the input files it will
be written to the output file. In this field you may specify the default
nutation model to be written to the pole output file header in case the
input files do not specify a model. Select a nutation model file.

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/IAU2000R06.NUT">$X/GEN/IAU2000R06.NUT</a>.

<a name="SUBMOD" default="IERS2010XY"></a>
<p><b>Subdaily pole model:</b>
Bernese ERP files specify the subdaily pole model used for the generation of
the file. If the corresponding string is found in the input files it will
be written to the output file. In this field you may specify the default
subdaily pole model to be written to the pole output file header in case the
input files do not specify a model. Select a subdaily pole model file.

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/IERS2010XY.SUB">$X/GEN/IERS2010XY.SUB</a>

<br><br>

<a name="NDAYS" default="1"></a>
<p><b>BULLETIN B AS INPUT</b>
<p><b>Use 1 or 5 day values:</b>
In the case you use the values of IERS Bulletin B you can select
whether you want to use the daily Earth Rotation Parameters or the
values given in a five day interval.
Enter <tt>1</tt> to select the daily values and <tt>5</tt> to select the
five day values. This field is only used if you specify Bulletin B as
input.

<p><i>Default value:</i>  <tt>1</tt>

<br><br>

<a name="USERATE" default="1"></a>
<p><b>OPTIONS</b>
<p><b>Use ERP rates:</b>
Option to use the ERP rates given in the IGS/IERS format to generate
additional pole records at the beginning and end of a day.
This option should, e.g., be used, if you convert IGS Rapid Pole files
(IGR), because these files only contain one record at 12:00 UT.
Enabling this option you obtain a Bernese pole file with
three records (at 0:00, 12:00, and 24:00 of the day) out of the IGR
pole file.

<p><i>Default value:</i> marked

<a name="DBLEPO" default="0"></a>
<p><b>Allow double epochs:</b>
The option allows to extract double epochs from input files in order
to convert all epochs in the input files. The option is only active if
ERP rates are not used.

<p><i>Default value:</i> unmarked

<a name="NUTOFF" default="0"></a>
<p><b>Include nutation offsets:</b>
Check this box if you want to copy nutation drifts from the input files to
the output Bernese file. If the IAU2000 nutation model is used drifts
(currently only available in Bulletin A or C04) are not needed.

<p><i>Default value:</i> unmarked

<a name="IWIN" default="0"></a>
<p><b>Use time window:</b>
Check this box to enter a time window for the pole records to be written into
the output file. Pole records outside the specified window will not be written.

<p><i>Default value:</i> unmarked

<p><hr>

<p><b>POLUPD 3: Time Window</b>

<a name="RADIO_1" default="1"></a>
<p><b>TIME WINDOW</b>
<p>
This panel allows to specify a time window. Only pole records
within this time window will be used written to the output file.
<br>
You may define the time window either by using session definitions, or by
explicitly specifying start and end times.

<a name="SESSION_YEAR" default="$Y+0"></a>
<a name="SESSION_STRG" default="$S+0"></a>
<p><b>Year and Session identifier:</b>
You may specify one session from the <a href="SESSIONS.HLP">session table</a>.
The boundaries of this session define the time window. If you use an
open session table the year has to be specified in addition to the session
identifier. If you use a fixed session table the year is read from the session
definition and the value in the panel is ignored.
<br>
It is possible to specify a range of sessions using the corresponding
menu variable (<tt>$S+-</tt>). In this case the time window starts at the
beginning of the first session of the range and stops at the end of the last
session of the range. If you use an open session table the year should also
be given with the range variable (<tt>$Y+-</tt>).

<p><i>Default values:</i> Year: <tt>$Y+0</tt> session: <tt>$S+0</tt>

<a name="RADIO_2" default="0"></a>
<a name="STADAT" default="$YMD_STR+0"></a>
<a name="STATIM" default="00 00 00"></a>
<a name="ENDDAT" default="$YMD_STR+0"></a>
<a name="ENDTIM" default="23 59 59"></a>
<p><b>Start and End times:</b>
Specify date and time for the begin and the end of the time window.
<br>
To specify a time window which is open on one side of the interval,
leave the corresponding input field for the start/end date empty. The
associated start/end time is then ignored.

<p><i>Default values for daily processing:</i> Start date: <tt>$YMD_STR+0</tt>,
start time: 00&nbsp;00&nbsp;00, end date: <tt>$YMD_STR+0</tt>,
end time: 23&nbsp;59&nbsp;59

<p><hr>

</body>
</html>
